section.section:
Of the 11 members:
1 shall be a physician with expertise in childhood hearing loss;
3 shall be from the field of education:
1 shall be from the Maryland Department of Health and Mental Hygiene;
1 shall be a mental health professional with expertise in the area of deafness;
2 shall be parents of hearing-impaired children;
1 shall be from the Maryland Association of the Deaf;
1 shall be an audiologist with expertise in childhood hearing loss; and
1 shall be from the Alexander Graham Bell Association of Maryland.

text.section:
The Advisory Council shall:
Advise the Department on the implementation of universal hearing screening of newborns and an early identification program and follow-up of hearing-impaired infants and infants who have a risk factor of developing a hearing impairment;
Provide consultation to the Department in the development of the program;
Make recommendations for operation of the program;
Advise the Department:
In setting standards for the program;
In monitoring and reviewing the program; and
In providing quality assurance for the program;
Advise the Department on the development of protocols to assist hospitals in implementing universal hearing screening of newborns;
Provide consultation to the Department in the establishment of an educational program for families, professionals, and the public that can be integrated with existing State and local education agency programs; and
Review any materials the Department may distribute to the public concerning hearing-impaired newborns and infants.
